def plot_img(image_data):
    image = image_data.reshape(28, 28)
    plt.imshow(image, cmap="binary")
    plt.axis("off")

Preprocessing¶

Scaling the data¶

Min- Max normalization

In [ ]:
train_images = train_images.reshape((60000, 28 * 28))  # flattening the 28x28 image into dim=1 (784,) vector (and over all images in the training set)
test_images = test_images.reshape((10000, 28 * 28))

train_images = train_images.astype("float32") / 255  # normalizing the data to the range [0,1] by min-max range, and casting it to float32
test_images = test_images.astype("float32") / 255

Making the neccesary function inorder to analyze the performace model¶

In [ ]:
def make_pred(model, x_test):
    y_pred = np.argmax(model.predict(x_test.reshape((-1, 28 * 28))), axis=1)
    return y_pred

def eval_model(y_pred , y_test):
    report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred,output_dict=True)
    return (report)
    
def loss_acc(history):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize=(15, 5))

    # Plot loss on the first subplot
    axes[0].plot(history['loss'], label='Training Loss')
    axes[0].plot(history['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss')
    axes[0].set_title('Training and Validation Loss')
    axes[0].set_xlabel('Epochs')
    axes[0].set_ylabel('Loss')
    axes[0].legend()

    # Plot accuracy on the second subplot
    axes[1].plot(history['accuracy'], label='Training Accuracy')
    axes[1].plot(history['val_accuracy'], label='Validation Accuracy')
    axes[1].set_title('Training and Validation Accuracy')
    axes[1].set_xlabel('Epochs')
    axes[1].set_ylabel('Accuracy')
    axes[1].legend()

There are many hyperparameters which can be tuned inorder to improve performance of the model.¶

  • change in the amount of hidden layers
  • change in the amount of neurons in each layer
  • changing the activation function
  • changing the loss function
  • changing the optimizer
  • changing the epochs
  • changing the batch size

however i will try to change:¶

  • hidden layers
  • neurons
  • epochs
  • batch size

1. model layout:¶

  • 784 -> relu (input layer)
  • 256 -> relu (hidden layer 1)
  • 128 -> relu (hidden layer 2)
  • 64 -> relu (hidden layer 3)
  • 32 -> relu (hidden layer 4)
  • 10 -> softmax (output layer)
  • epoch -> 50
  • batch_size -> 256

Started with the most complex model and follwing the pyramid structure¶

Also keeping the number of neurons in the input layer as the number of columns in the data¶

model1 = Sequential([
        Dense(x_train.shape[1], activation='relu',input_shape=(x_train.shape[1],)),
        Dense(256, activation='relu'),
        Dense(128, activation='relu'),

    ])

model1.summary()

history1 = model1.fit(x_train,y_train, epochs=50 , batch_size=256,validation_data=(x_val, y_val))
